# Closing a dirty buffer pops the Save / Discard / Cancel overlay; Cancel keeps
# the buffer (still dirty), Discard drops it (falling back to the other buffer).
# (The overlay's text is "<name> has unsaved changes." — distinct from the
# "discarded unsaved changes" toast Discard leaves behind.)
write keep.txt the keeper
open keep.txt
write notes.txt first line
open notes.txt
expect pane "notes.txt"
expect dirty false

type  more text
expect dirty true

# Cancel: the overlay shows, `c` dismisses it, the buffer stays dirty.
command buffer.close
expect screen contains "has unsaved changes"
key c
expect screen lacks "has unsaved changes"
expect dirty true
expect pane "notes.txt"

# Discard: `d` drops the buffer and we land back on keep.txt.
command buffer.close
expect screen contains "has unsaved changes"
key d
expect pane "keep.txt"
expect screen contains "the keeper"
expect screen lacks "has unsaved changes"
